doctype html
- var bgr = './static/slides/bgr/bgr_12.jpg'
include ./partial/header.pug
include ./partial/title.pug
include ./partial/containers.pug
include ./partial/texts.pug

+header('MI-APH - Lecture12', 'Lecture 12: Indie Game Development', 'lecture12')
// ===================================================== SLIDES =====================================================
.reveal
  .slides
    // ============================================================
    +msection(bgr)
      .lecture-logo.mb80
        include ../static/slides/svg/lecture12/lecture12_logo.svg
      +title('Indie Games Development')
    // ============================================================
    +mcontainer(bgr)    
      h3 Literature
      ul
        li
          a(href='https://www.amazon.com/Level-Guide-Great-Video-Design/dp/1118877160') Rogers, Scott. 2015. Level Up! The Guide to Great Video Game Design 
      .center-content
          img(src!='../static/slides/images/lecture12/book_levelup.jpg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe-statement(bgr, 'Game Development')
      p.highlight At the very beginning, there was an idea. And a naive dreamer said: <br>"Shall we transform the idea to a computer game." <br>And it was so. And it was 
        span.crossed good
        span.highlight-sec &nbsp;a nightmare.
    // ============================================================
    +chapter(bgr, 'Design')
    // ============================================================
    +mcontainer(bgr)
      h3 Game Design
      .rows-3.mt100
        .frame-sticky.w65.h300
          p Game Design is the act of deciding what a game should be. That's it. On the surface, it sounds too simple. The voyage of discovery is not in seeking new landscapes but in having new eyes.
          p.highlight-third.tright Jesse Schell
        .frame-sticky.w45.h250.l800
          p Most gamers don't know what they want until it is shown to them.
          p.highlight-third.tright Scott Rogers
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Game development professions')
      h4 Programmer 
      ul
        li designs and implements the SW 
        li runtime programmers (work on the engine)
        li tool programmers (offline tools)
        li GFX developers, AI specialists, gameplay coders,...
      h4 Artist 
      ul
        li concept artist - sketches, paintings 
        li 3D modelers, texture artists, lightning artists, animators, composers,...
      h4 Designer 
      ul
        li gameplay designers 
        li level designers (static geometry, supplies, puzzle elements, window aspects)
      h4 Other Staff 
      ul
        li Testing department
        li Marketing department 
        li publisher, creative manager, art director, technical director,...
    // ============================================================
    +mcontainer(bgr)
      h3 Game Design Document
      .rows-3
        .frame-sticky.w60.h200
          +strtext('A design document is a', 'bible', 'from which the producer preaches the goal, through which the designers reflect their ideas.')
          p.highlight-third.tright Gamasutra (1999)
        .frame-sticky.w55.h200.l400
          p A design document should be just long enough to accurately describe what is going on in the game. 
          p.highlight-third.tright Scott Rogers (2010)
        .frame-sticky.w45.h200.l800
          +strtext('A design document is', 'the blueprint', 'from which a game is to be built.')
          p.highlight-third.tright Game Developer Blog (2016)
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Game Design Document')
      ul
        li there are no official formats nor rules how to write the GDD 
        li in recent years, wiki is used more frequently than printed GDD 
        li.mt40
          span.highlight game design is a highly iterative process
          ul
            li it is nearly impossible to predict the behavior of a game before implementation
            li common agile processes: Scrum and SAFe
        li.mt40
          span.highlight GDD content:
          ul
            li working title 
            li.highlight-sec gameplay and intended mechanics 
            li target audience 
            li story, campaigns, modes (DM, CTF, TDM,...)
            li characters
            li ESRB/PEGI ratings 
            li unique selling points 
            li competitive products 
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Design structures')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/script_gta.jpg')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.mt100.mr350.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/level_rayman.jpg')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.mt400.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/tables.jpg')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.mt450.mr350.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/window_prince.jpg')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.mt650.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/map_guild_wars2.jpg')
      ul.highlight
        li Story and script 
        li.mt150 Level structure
        li.mt150 Tables (skills, abilities, upgrades,...)
        li.mt150 Window elements, surprise elements, puzzles,... 
        li.mt150 Game map
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Story')
      .columns-2
        figure
          img.h400(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/story_doom.jpg')
          p Doom
        figure
          img.h400(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/story_fear.jpg')
          p F.E.A.R.
      ul.mt40
        li a story is a background aspect of a gameplay and gameplay is a medium used to tell a story
        li.mt40.highlight good gameplay can overshadow a terrible story
        li.highlight good story can't really overshadow a terrible gameplay 
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Hero')
      .top-content.justify-left
        img.h300.mt150(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_arthas.gif')
      .top-content.justify-left
        img.h300.mt200.ml800(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_crash.png')
      .top-content.justify-left
        img.h300.mt550.ml200(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_doomguy.gif')
      .bottom-content.fill.justify-left
        img.h300.ml600(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_freeman.png')
      .top-content
        img.h300.mt350.mr450(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_jazz.png')
      .bottom-content
        img.h300.ml300(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_keen.gif')
      .bottom-content
        img.h300.ml900(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_mario.png')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.h300.mt100.ml700(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_rayman.gif')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.h300.mt250.mr300(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_skyrim.png')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.h300.mt600(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/hero_sonic.gif')
      ul
        li very important and often unjustly neglected element of games 
        li
          +strtext('', 'Main attributes:', 'name, appearance, facial proportions, movement, humanity')
        li
          +strtext('', 'Archetypes:', 'humorous character, heroic character, villain character')
    // ============================================================
    +mcontainer(bgr)
      h3 Example: Prince of Persia 2
      .center-content
        img.w100(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/pop.jpg')
      .mt60.ml40
        a.pop(href='http://www.jordanmechner.com/downloads/pop2bible.pdf') http://www.jordanmechner.com/downloads/pop2bible.pdf
    // ============================================================
    +chapter(bgr, 'Indie Games')
    // ============================================================
    +mcontainer(bgr)
      h3 Indie games
      .rows-3
        .frame-sticky.w55.h200
          p.highlight Indie game is a video game that is often created without a financial support of a publisher. 
        .frame-sticky.w55.h200.l400
          p.highlight-sec Indie games are developed by individuals, small teams or small independent companies, having little to no budget available.
        .frame-sticky.w55.h200.l800
          p.highlight-third Indie games are games that are smaller in size, less taxing on hardware and focusing mostly on art design.
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Categories of games')
      .columns-3.center-content
        div
          img.h500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/games_casual.png') 
        div
          img.h500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/games_indie.png') 
        div
          img.h500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/games_aaa.png')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Game costs')
      .tcenter
        img.h900(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/cost_of_games.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Milestones')
      .tcenter
        img.h800(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/indie_milestones.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Indie Games Evolution')
      .top-content
        img.h650.mt150(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/indie_games.png')
      .top-content
        img.h800(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/indie_games.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'AAA vs Indie')
      .columns-3.center-content
        figure
          img.h350(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/aaa_cutedge.jpg')
          p Cutting-edge graphics
        figure
          img.h350(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/aaa_studios.jpg')
          p Large studios
        figure
          img.h350(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/aaa_campaign.jpg')
          p Massive campaigns
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'AAA vs Indie')
      h4 Indie game developer
      ul
        li must span a huge number of various subject areas 
        li the less resources you have, the more creative you need to be
        li animation, textures, cinematography, music, sound effects, creative writing, visual arts,...
      h4.mt40 AAA game developer 
      ul
        li is usually specialized in one or a few areas 
        li skeletal animation, sprite animation, particle systems, physics, scripting, dialogue trees, backend (matchmaking, updates, in-game transactions)
        li making AAA is about delegating tasks to huge teams 
        li.highlight-sec there isn't a lot of space for own expression
        li 
          span.highlight-third many AAA devs eventually go indie 
          ul
            li Jade Raymond - left Ubisoft in 2014
            li Cliff Bleszinski - left Epic Games in 2012, started his own studio 
            li Brian Reynolds - SM Civilization designer, started his own studio
    // ============================================================
    +chapter(bgr, 'Game Industry today')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Global revenues')
      .tcenter
        img.h800.mr200(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/revenues.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Games released on Steam')
      .tcenter
        img.h900(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/steam.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Game developer in 2010')
      .tcenter
        img.h900(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/dev_in_2010.png')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Game Developer in 2019')
      .top-content.justify-left
        img.h850(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/dev_today_01.jpg')
      .top-content.justify-right
        img.w900(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/dev_today_02.jpg')
      .bottom-content.justify-right
        img.w900.mb60(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/dev_today_03.jpg')
      .center-content
        img.h400(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/fb_01.jpg')
      .top-content.justify-left.mt200.ml80
        img.h350(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/fb_02.jpg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Game industry crisis')
      ul
        li we have 2.3 billions gamers across the globe 
        li game industry earn more money than ever before 
        li.highlight it is easier than ever to develop a game 
        li.highlight-sec it is harder than ever to develop a successful game 
        li.mt20
          span.highlight-third Issues:
          ul
            li low median ownership (number of players per each game)
            li disruptive technology (game developers just glue components together)
            li low barrier of entry (everyone can create a game, reading a tutorial)
            li lack of differentiation (do we need next 100 pixel-art platformers?) 
      .tcenter
        img.h350(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/indie_crisis.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Marketing')
      ul
        li marketing may cover up to 50% of all expenses
        li there is nothing like a self-selling game
      .tcenter.mt40
        img.h600(src='../static/slides/svg/lecture12/indie_marketing.svg')
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Is it worth it?')
      .article
        a.t150.l150(href='http://gingearstudio.com/why-i-quit-my-dream-job-at-ubisoft')
          img.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/article_ubisoft.jpg')
      .article
        a.t300.l150(href='https://www.gamasutra.com/blogs/AdrielWallick/20140226/211761/Make_Many_Games_Learn_Many_Things.php')
          img.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/article_games.jpg')
      .article
        a.t400.l150(href='https://www.reddit.com/r/gamedev/comments/dwfwtp/three_years_ago_my_wife_and_i_quit_our_jobs_to/')
          img.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/article_ninefaced.png')
      .article
        a.t600.l150(href='https://enterprisecraftsmanship.com/posts/how-i-tried-to-get-into-game-development-and-failed/')
          img.w500(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/article_khorikov.jpg')
      ul
        li to make a game, it can take several years of a very hard work and suffering  
        li it is a world with many heroes, a few stars and very few superstars
      .tcenter
        img.h600.ml250(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/kingdom_come.jpg')
        p.highlight-third Leaving a footprint of your work in the mind of players and the passionate involvement from the development itself is the most valuable reward every game developer should aspire to. 
    // ============================================================
    +mframe(bgr, 'Goodbye sheet')
      .top-content
        img.h900(src='../static/slides/images/lecture12/sheet.png') 
      h4.fragment.fade-in Prince of Persia
            
include ./partial/footer.pug
